    <example xml:id="auto_81m0anr3">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_42syfuw9">
                Kakamega town's population doubles every 10 years. If the population today is 50,000 people, what will it's population be in 30 years time?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_uxi6tx2y">
                Since the population doubles every <m>10</m> years, we observe the following:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8jt57umu">
                <ul xml:id="auto_ppfepcyh">
                    <li xml:id="auto_avogrqwp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_b4fbqhli">
                            After <m>10</m> years  →  <m>50, 000 \times 2</m> = <m>100, 000</m> people
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_n7xnevf2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vg94zvl8">
                            After <m>20</m> years  →  <m>100, 000 \times 2</m> = <m>200, 000</m> people
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_dvb6o410">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d5tg30tw">
                            After <m>30</m> years  →  <m>200, 000 \times 2</m> = <m>400, 000</m> people
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6kboz9qt">
                Instead of calculating step by step, we can use indices.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wapfl2ej">
                Since the population doubles every <m>10</m> years, we use the exponential growth model:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_afkhtzok">
                <me>
                     P = P_0 \times P^{\frac {t}{10}}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0rrsen8e">
                Where:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_s17atzui">
                <ul xml:id="auto_odgqxnrf">
                    <li xml:id="auto_my3xm2fc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5cyc7vav">
                            <m>P</m> = population after <m>t</m> years
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mrl11kqo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7wxaj6aa">
                            <m>P_0</m> = Initial population <m>(50 000)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0mf7jmte">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nnjnk6c8">
                            <m>t</m> = number of years <m>(30)</m> years
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vlcegk4n">
                        <p xml:id="auto_y2xcmyd0">
                            The base <m>2</m> represents doubling every <m>10</m> years
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_2e4oud6z">
                Therefore:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fyn651eq">
                <me> P = 50 000 \times  2^{\frac {30}{10}}</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9o8rhyev">
                Since <m>\frac {30}{10} =3,</m> we simplify:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nlkgv2hu">
                <me> P = 50 000 \times  2^3</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qn3ikh0k">
                We now calculate <m>2^3</m> ;
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_v03q0v71">
                <me>
                    2^3 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 = 8
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vzzkd7nl">
                Now,
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3yb70vvs">
                <me>P = 50, 000 \times 8</me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ye17bryu">
                <me>
                    = 400, 000
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7ag517uv">
                In <m>30</m> years time, the town's population will be <m>400,000</m> people
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

